        "cooked": "<p>The verification message you currently send is:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>SIGNAL code: XXXXXX. Do not share this code with anyone. If anyone asks, it’s SCAM. Our reps will NEVER ask for it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The positive feedback first: a lot of companies (like banks) should learn about this approach: just say directly as it is and use the word scam (instead of saying “malicious party might compromise your account if you do not follow the instructions” or similar BS which banks use).</p>\n<p>Then, the improvement suggestion: professional communication should not include spoken language like “it’s” and “reps”. If I counted correctly, the SMS character limit does not hinder you saying:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>SIGNAL code: XXXXXX. Do not share this code with anyone. If anyone asks, it is a SCAM. Our staff will NEVER ask for it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This sounds more professional and non-native speakers don’t have to google what is “reps”.</p>",
